message: If we go to Washington together, you can be sure that there will be a lot of discussions about more progressive approaches to policy issues, but I'm not fooling myself. Moe is his own man and he will do what he believes is right for his district.

name: David Wilson Brown
message:
It applies to any hospital that takes Medicare funds, which is virtually every hospital in the country. So, we already have a national health care mandate, but it's a largely unfunded one. Let's do this thing right.
I support #MedicareForAll #M4A  13/13 https://t.co/imt38Ng6lz

name: David Wilson Brown
message: You see, thanks to Ronald Reagan, we have the Emergency Medical Treatment & Active Labor Act. This 1986 law requires hospitals to treat patients in need of emergency care regardless of their ability to pay, citizenship or even legal status. 12/13

name: David Wilson Brown
message: A single-payer system will be able to reduce the overall cost for care. A single-payer system will allow people to go to primary care doctors first for wellness and prevention, greatly reducing our nation's overall costs and reduce the stress on our Emergency Rooms. 11/13

name: David Wilson Brown
message: A single-payer system would make sure all Americans have coverage. It would greatly reduce the costs of managing billing for hospitals and doctors offices across this nation. A single-payer system that is not driven by profit will not deny you care when you need it. 10/13

name: David Wilson Brown
message: Prior to passage of the ACA, it was common for providers to stop covering customers once they got sick ‚Äì something the insurers called ‚Äúrescissions.‚Äù This is why coverage of pre-existing conditions is so important... and out of greed, GOP wants to end those protections. 9/13

name: David Wilson Brown
message: One commenter right here on Twitter insisted that "Healthcare isn't a right. I don't have the right to spend other people's money on my healthcare." But that is EXACTLY what insurance is if your needs exceed what you pay in. I haven't paid in 300k to my health insurance. 8/13

name: David Wilson Brown
message: Moving to a single-payer, taxpayer-provided healthcare system is the only logical and best financial option for our nation. What is insurance other than combining resources to hedge your bet that you won't need more than the combined premiums paid in can cover. 7/13

name: David Wilson Brown
message: This pandemic has exposed the fragility of having our insurance tied to our employment. It suggests that only someone employed deserves to have health coverage. What if you are a stay-at-home mom or dad? With our schools closed, many had to be. 6/13

name: David Wilson Brown
message: We have COBRA, but to maintain one‚Äôs insurance through COBRA, you must pay the ENTIRE insurance premium, including the portion previously paid by the employer. Having no income but unemployment insurance, which often covers only a portion of your pay, how can you afford it? 5/13

name: David Wilson Brown
message: During the pandemic, 40 million Americans were furloughed or flat out lost their jobs. So in the middle of a national health crisis, Americans lost the jobs that provided them and their families their health coverage. 4/13

name: David Wilson Brown
message: I actually ran in my primary race while I was recovering. Staffers had to drive me and I never did events over a couple of hours. In the end, I won my primary election on March 3rd. A week later, the initial lockdowns for COVID hit. 3/13

name: David Wilson Brown
message: I thought about all the folks who might have been in my situation without the kind of insurance I had. My total bill would have been nearly 300k. That's more than most folks houses, if they are home owners. How much would the cost hurt their family financially? 2/13

name: David Wilson Brown
message: I had a heart-attack on Christmas Eve last year. Two days later, I underwent quadruple bypass surgery. I was fortunate to have excellent private insurance through my employer, but as I was in ICU for ten days, I thought about more than just recovering. 1/13 https://t.co/TDfwbuQBM7

name: David Wilson Brown
message:
If you believe these policies regarding accountability and transparency that I feel are critical to restoring the public trust in our government officials are important to you and you live in #NC05, I humbly ask for your vote this election. 
15/15

name: David Wilson Brown
message: This last point is important to me. I seek to ensure there is no room for even the question of self-dealing or personal enrichment to exist. I will be in DC to serve the people of my district. Period. /14

name: David Wilson Brown
message: 5. I will place my family‚Äôs savings into a blind trust and accept no funds from the U.S. government (other than my earned paycheck) or funds from the governments of any state or local municipality during the period of my tenure. /13

name: David Wilson Brown
message: 4. I will hold publicly accessible in-person town hall meetings throughout the district every House recess period of a week or more. I will not be a Member of Congress who you only see photos of private meetings after the fact. /12

name: David Wilson Brown
message:
3. I will release a weekly address to my district while Congress is in session detailing:
*What the House did last week
*What the House has on its agenda for this week
*What I feel are hindrances to delivering the best result for our district. /11

name: David Wilson Brown
message: 2. I will require any special interest group that wants to meet with me to convince at least one constituent to come to DC to join that meeting. I want to underscore in the business that I do regarding my job as a legislature is focused on serving the people of my district. /10

name: David Wilson Brown
message: 1. I will publish my office visitor logs online for all constituents to be able to see who I am meeting with. I know tech and I know how to deliver this. /9

name: David Wilson Brown
message: Again, I'm not suggesting she was doing anything most of the others were doing, it was just eye opening about how our Congress works. So that experience has influenced policies I would like to put into place when I take office. /8

name: David Wilson Brown
message: I saw the frequency that she met with lobbyists, which I have no doubt was the norm across both parties. But it always struck me with how rarely she was meeting with actual constituents. It was the summer and I was there for only 3 months, but it was noticeable. /7

name: David Wilson Brown
message:
I was lone Democrat among the staff (they used this to their advantage at one point to call a project "bipartisan") and the way other Dems were referenced was usually pretty derogatory. I have a specific memory of them mocking Barney Frank for being openly gay.
 /6

name: David Wilson Brown
message:
My biggest takeaways were that working there meant not making much of a salary despite the high cost of living in DC area and a high level of toxicity between the parties. You have to remember this was during Gingrich's revolution.
/5

name: David Wilson Brown
message: I'd take notes and report back. I remember at least once I got to submit a more formal policy recommendation, although I cannot remember on what nor do I know if she ever saw it. /4

name: David Wilson Brown
message:
But I also had the opportunity to attend hearings and informational sessions about policies that related to her committee assignments: science, small business, and housing.
So I attended meetings on Fannie Mae/Freddie Mac, the internet, and the International Space Station. /3

name: David Wilson Brown
message:
I don't pretend that it alone makes me "qualified" to serve in Congress, only that it gives me some partial insight into how things work there.
As an intern, I mostly did things like answer the phone, process mail, and give tours of the Capitol to constituents.
/2
